\begin_layout Section
Consumer Theory: Comparative Statics / Sensitivity Analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Changes in Income
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When talking about how consumers (not consciously) solve the consumption
 problem, we rely on the households attempting to maximize utility, and
 usually convex utility functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
ICC
\series default
 is the income-consumption curve (in the consumption bundle space) - income
 is not represented.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Engel
\series default
 curve is in the income-good (quantity) space - other goods are not represented
 - focuses on a particular product.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another way to think of it - a 3-dimensional graph, with 2 goods being the
 
\begin_inset Formula $X,Y$
\end_inset

 axes and the income being the 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 axis.
 Each point represents an affordable consumption bundle, given some level
 of income.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The ICC curve is the projection of that graph so that optimal bundles are
 seen as a curve.
 The Engel curve is another projection, that shows the relation between
 income and one of the good.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
ICC for CD Preferences
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The ICC curve is a ray from the origin.
 Using a Cobb-Douglas utility function, the optimal spendings on 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are given by 
\begin_inset Formula $a\frac{1}{p_{x}}I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-a)\frac{1}{p_{y}}I$
\end_inset

 thus the slope is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{y}{x}=\frac{1-a}{a}=\frac{p_{x}}{p_{y}}
\]

\end_inset

Perferences are 
\series bold
homothetic
\series default
 - slopes of the IC's are equal along each single ray.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Engel Curve
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Considering the optimal solution, this curve focuses on the demand of some
 particular good and its change as income changes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Income Elasticity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The degree of responsiveness of the demand, as the result of change in income.
 The partial derivatie 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial x}{\partial I}$
\end_inset

 depends on the unit of measurement, thus isnot very meaningful (change
 of the unit would affect it).
 In order to clean it, we divide (normalize) it
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eta_{xI}=\frac{\frac{\parallel x}{\partial I}}{\frac{x}{I}}=\frac{\frac{a}{p_{x}}}{\frac{a}{p_{x}}}=1
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{xI}\equiv1$
\end_inset

 iff the demand for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a linear function of income.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A constant elasciticy example: when 
\begin_inset Formula $z=aw^{c}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eta_{z,w}=\frac{acw^{c-1}}{aw^{c-1}}=c
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Goods can be distinguished according to their elasticity:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{x,I}>0$
\end_inset

 A
\series bold
 normal
\series default
 good (the more income you have - the more of it you buy)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{x,I}=0$
\end_inset


\series bold
 
\series default
A 
\series bold
neutral
\series default
 good
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{x,I}<0$
\end_inset

 An 
\series bold
inferior 
\series default
good.
 The consumption decreases as the income increases, 
\series bold
in a certain range
\series default
.
 Why 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

in a certain range
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 - there must be a solution for zero income and it can't be negative (the
 consumption level has first to increase as the income increases, so that
 it has where to decrease from).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is possible to further distinct goods with positive elasticity:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{x,I}>1$
\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
luxur
\series default
y good - not only that the consumption increases when income increases,
 but the 
\series bold
portion of income
\series default
 which is devoted to thers goods 
\series bold
increases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{x,I}=1$
\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
proportional
\series default
 good - as income increases, 
\series bold
the same
\series default
 portion of income is used to consume it
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{x,I}<1$
\end_inset

 An 
\series bold
essential
\series default
 good
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For CD preference function, we found out that the elasticity equals 1 -
 meaning that a 1% increase in income will result in 1% increase of expenditure
 on a good.
 That makes sense, as when ahving two goods with one of them having elasticity
 of 1 - the other one must have this elasticity as well (can be shown algebrical
ly).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More generally - the 
\series bold
weighted avergage
\series default
 of the elasticities of the goods must always be 1 ( e.gall goods cannot
 be luxury goods).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Consumer Theory: Changes in Price
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the price of a good changes, the lines depicting the budget constraint
 change (slope is changed, because axis intersection given by 
\begin_inset Formula $I/p$
\end_inset

 moves to a new point).
 Several graphs are used to explore this change:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
PCC (Price Consumption Curve)
\series default
 - in the 
\series bold
bundles
\series default
 space (no representation of price).
 A flat line (moving across various consumption bundles by changing a price
 of one good, when the income and the other price are fixed).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Demand curve
\series default
 - shows the 
\series bold
price-quantity 
\series default
relation (no representation of the other goods).
 Defines the demand for the good at each given price, and allows to find
 out the optimization point of price times quantitiy (revenue maximization
 for a monopoly).
 When elasticity is 1, the resulting plot line is a hyperbola.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Cross demand curve
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The the demand curve is generally downward sloping.
 Consider a price increase: the budget line becomes 
\series bold
tighter
\series default
, and its slope changes (because the 
\series bold
price ratio
\series default
 has changed).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Income
\series default
 and 
\series bold
substitution
\series default
 effects: when a price rises, the consumer 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

becomes poorer
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Consider an example: a price of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 increases, but the consuemr gets extra money for having the same amount
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 he used to have.
 He 
\series bold
would not
\series default
 do it, becuase the new budget constraint has another slope, leading to
 a choice with lower amount of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 (
\series bold
Slutsky
\series default
 compensation) - as he is now allowed to consume 
\series bold
other
\series default
 bundles (some of them give them 
\series bold
more utility
\series default
).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Hicks
\series default
 compensation: bring the customer to the same 
\series bold
indifference curve
\series default
 i.e only give enough money to make him able to consume bundles that correspond
 to the same utility he used to have, before the price raise.
 Hicks compensation is more fair, but is much more complicated to implement
 in practice (requires knowledge & calculations).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
substitition effect
\series default
 can never be positive: price increase won't make a consumer want to buy
 more of it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Income effect
\series default
: when a price increases, the result is the same as if the income decreased.
 The income effect is negative / zero / positive, depends on whether the
 good is normal / neutral / inferior.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a 
\series bold
normal
\series default
 good, the income and substitution effects are in the 
\series bold
same
\series default
 direction.
 For 
\series bold
inferior
\series default
 goods, they act in 
\series bold
opposit
\series default
 directions.
 The substitution effect was empirically shown to be usually stronger.
 Giffen goods must not be confused with 
\series bold
uncertainity
\series default
 regarding quality, or with 
\series bold
conspicious consumption
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Endowments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is no 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

income
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in a general equilibrium, but only an 
\series bold
initial endowment
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Defining 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x},\hat{y}$
\end_inset

 as initial endowments of good 1 and 2, the budget constraint can be rewritten:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I=p_{x}x+p_{y}y=p_{x}\hat{x}+p_{y}\hat{y}\Rightarrow p_{x}(x-\hat{x})=p_{y}(\hat{y}-y)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Graphically, it means that we are given a particular point on the budget
 constraint line.
 In order to optimize, a consumer might pick another bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x<\hat{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y>\hat{y}$
\end_inset

.
 Would she then prefer to trade 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, or the opposite? 
\series bold
Depends
\series default
 on the 
\series bold
preferences
\series default
 (slope of the IC curve).
 For any given budget it is possible to find preferences for both cases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also, given preferences - 
\series bold
typically
\series default
 prices can be found for both options as well.
\end_layout

