Example
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define: 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}=10,\,\hat{y}=10,\,U(x,y)=2log(x)+log(y)$
\end_inset

 and the prices are 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{x}=3,\,p_{y}=1$
\end_inset

 meaning 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is (relatively) expensive.
 Then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I=30+10=40\Rightarrow x=8.88,\,y=13.33
\]

\end_inset

Supply extra units of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $10-8.88=1.11$
\end_inset

) and demand 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $13.33-10=3.33$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Markets and Equilibria
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume that there is no production, everyone is a price-taker and there
 are many (2 - can be generalized) consumers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given two consumers and their preferences functions, we can put them in
 
\series bold
Edgeworth's box
\series default
 - a graphical representation of the preferences of both of them on a single
 plane.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Pareto domination
\series default
 - there is a domination of some allocation over another one iff the utility
 of both consumers in the first one is 
\series bold
at least
\series default
 as good as in the second one, and the utility of at least one of them is
 
\series bold
strictly
\series default
 better.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Pareto Optimality / Efficiency
\series default
 - an allocation is Pareto-optimal if there is no feasible allocation which
 as Pareto dominance over it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Considering the Edgeworth's box - the optimal allocation is at the points
 where the indifference curves are tangent.
 Several Pareto-efficient allocations might exist.
 They are connected by a 
\series bold
contract curve
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
utility frontier
\series default
 corresponds to all 
\series bold
Pareto optimal
\series default
 allocations.
 Notice that Pareto domination is incomplete, as it doesn't provide a means
 to compare 
\series bold
any
\series default
 two allocations (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

order relation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Equilibrium
\series default
 is a list of prices, such that when 
\series bold
everyone
\series default
 responds optimally to them - markets 
\series bold
clear
\series default
 (no excess demand, excess supply only for zero-price).
 In general there are also 
\series bold
firms
\series default
 which take part in the market by demanding labor, supplying output and
 dividing profit - but first an equilibrium 
\series bold
without firms
\series default
 will be considered.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Existence theorem: (under certain assumptions) 
\series bold
there exists at least one competitive equilibrium
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the 2x2 case it can me (misleadingly) graphically shown by plotting the
 budget lines and tilting them with price changes.
 An important property: at equilibrium both ICs are tangent to the same
 line, thus 
\series bold
to each other
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
